## Step 1 – Quick filename search

Open PowerShell as Administrator, then copy and run these three commands (one at a time or as a script). They’ll check the most likely locations:

```powershell
# Check default Bitcoin Core data folder
Test-Path "$env:APPDATA\Bitcoin\wallet.dat"

# Search your "Crypto" desktop folder for wallet.dat
Get-ChildItem -Path "C:\Users\Alex\Desktop\Crypto" -Recurse -Filter wallet.dat -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-Object FullName

# Search the entire external drive E:\ for wallet.dat
Get-ChildItem -Path "E:\" -Recurse -Filter wallet.dat -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-Object FullName
```

If any of those return a path, you’ve found your wallet file. Note the full path, and we’ll move on.

## Step 2 – Fingerprint‑based fallback (only if Step 1 finds nothing)

If `wallet.dat` wasn’t found, the file may have been renamed but still **is** a Bitcoin Core wallet. We’ll scan all `*.dat` files in both locations for the Berkeley DB magic bytes (`00 06 15 61`). This can take a while on a large drive.

Run this PowerShell snippet:

```powershell
$magic = @(0x00,0x06,0x15,0x61)

function Test-BerkeleyDB {
    param([string]$file)
    try {
        $bytes = [System.IO.File]::ReadAllBytes($file)
        if ($bytes.Length -ge 4) {
            for ($i=0;$i -lt 4;$i++) {
                if ($bytes[$i] -ne $magic[$i]) { return $false }
            }
            return $true
        }
    } catch {}
    return $false
}

$paths = @("C:\Users\Alex\Desktop\Crypto","E:\")
foreach ($p in $paths) {
    Get-ChildItem -Path $p -Recurse -Filter *.dat -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | ForEach-Object {
        if (Test-BerkeleyDB $_.FullName) { $_.FullName }
    }
}
```

If any files are listed, they are strong candidates for your Bitcoin Core wallet.

